| mutating a nested struct requires a separate package and metaprogramming hacks.<p>But it doesn&#x27;t. And you would have known this if only you had read the fucking article.<p><pre><code>    data Position = Position { x :: Int, y :: Int }
    data Player = Player { pos :: Position }

    moveRight :: Int -> Player -> Player
    moveRight n (Player (Position x y)) = Player (Position (x + n) y)</code></pre>

javascript &quot;module&quot; dependencies are written in javascript, not in html renderer.<p>in development:<p><pre><code>    <script data-main=&quot;your-module.js&quot; src=&quot;require.js&quot;></script>
</code></pre>
in production:<p><pre><code>    <script src=&quot;your-module.min.js&quot;></script>
</code></pre>
One problem I haven&#x27;t solved is when html renderer writes inputs to your javascript module. I can either print my module&#x27;s main body in html:<p><pre><code>    <script>
        require([&#x27;yourModule&#x27;], function(yourModule) {
            var config = {% server template vars %};
            yourModule.start(config);
        });
    </script>
</code></pre>
Or use global config variable and shim.
